 Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Madog ap Rhys was born in Saint Asaph, Flintshire, Wales, United Kingdom as the son of Makintosh. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter."},"et":{"–":"Surnud","1449–Female":"1449–Surnud","1454–Male":"1454–Surnud","1500–Female":"1500–Surnud","–1630":"–1630","–Female":"Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1370–Male":"1370–Surnud","1437–Male":"1437–Surnud","1437":"1437","1500":"1500","1630":"1630","1454":"1454","1370":"1370","1449":"1449","of,Llanelwy,Flintshire,Wales":"Saint Asaph, Flintshire, Wales, United Kingdom","{Edwin}":"Edwin, Prantsuse Guajaana"},"fi":{"–":"Kuollut","1449–Female":"1449–Kuollut","1454–Male":"1454–Kuollut","1500–Female":"1500–Kuollut","–1630":"–1630","–Female":"Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1370–Male":"1370–Kuollut","1437–Male":"1437–Kuollut","1437":"1437","1500":"1500","1630":"1630","1454":"1454","1370":"1370","1449":"1449","of,Llanelwy,Flintshire,Wales":"Saint Asaph, Flintshire, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","{Edwin}":"Edwin, Ranskan Guayana"},"fr":{"–":"Décédé","1449–Female":"